# Salesforce MCP Configuration (Optional)
#
# The Salesforce MCP server uses SF CLI authentication by default.
# These environment variables are OPTIONAL overrides.

# ============================================================================
# OPTIONAL: Specify default target org
# ============================================================================
# If not set, uses the default org from SF CLI (`sf config get target-org`)
# SF_TARGET_ORG=my-sandbox

# ============================================================================
# CI/CD: JWT Authentication (Service Accounts)
# ============================================================================
# For automated environments, use JWT-based authentication
# SF_CLIENT_ID=your_connected_app_consumer_key
# SF_JWT_KEY_FILE=/path/to/private-key.pem
# SF_USERNAME=service-account@company.com

# ============================================================================
# CI/CD: Direct Token Authentication (Less Secure)
# ============================================================================
# Only use in controlled CI environments with proper secret management
# SF_ACCESS_TOKEN=your_access_token
# SF_INSTANCE_URL=https://your-instance.salesforce.com

# ============================================================================
# NOTES
# ============================================================================
# 1. For local development, DO NOT use these variables
#    - Just authenticate with: sf org login web --alias my-org
#    - The MCP server will use your SF CLI session
#
# 2. For team collaboration:
#    - Each developer authenticates separately
#    - No shared credentials needed
#
# 3. For CI/CD pipelines:
#    - Use JWT authentication (most secure)
#    - Store credentials in CI secret manager (GitHub Secrets, etc.)
#
# 4. Security:
#    - NEVER commit this file with real values
#    - .env files are ignored by .gitignore
#    - Use service accounts for automation, not personal accounts
